  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Negative gearing is widely understood as a strategy for reducing your taxable income while holding an investment property. What is less well understood is what happens to that arrangement when you sell. The answer is important: the negative gearing benefit stops the moment the property is no longer income-producing, and the capital gains tax calculation that follows can significantly affect your net result from the sale. Brisbane investors who have held property for years sometimes reach settlement with a figure that looks strong on the surface but is considerably smaller after the ATO has taken its share.</p>

      <p>This article explains how negative gearing and CGT interact at the point of sale, what the 12-month CGT discount means in practice, and why involving a tax accountant before you go to market is not optional if you want to make a financially informed decision.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What negative gearing actually is</h2>
      <p>A property is negatively geared when the costs of holding it (mortgage interest, council rates, insurance, property management fees, repairs, and depreciation) exceed the rental income it generates. The resulting loss is an assessable tax deduction against your other income, typically your salary. For investors on a high marginal tax rate, this deduction can meaningfully reduce their annual tax bill while the property appreciates in value.</p>

      <p>The strategy is based on the expectation that capital growth will more than compensate for the annual cash shortfall. Over a long hold period in Brisbane's inner east, that expectation has generally proven correct. But the tax outcome on the way in and the tax outcome on the way out are two entirely separate calculations, and confusing them is one of the more costly mistakes property investors make.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to negative gearing when you sell</h2>
      <p>When you sell the property, negative gearing stops. There is no rental income, no holding costs to offset, and no further deduction. The sale event triggers a capital gains tax assessment instead. These are two different parts of the tax system and they do not offset each other. The losses you have claimed year-on-year as income tax deductions do not reduce your capital gain at sale time.</p>

      <p>Your capital gain is calculated as the sale price minus the cost base. The cost base generally includes the original purchase price plus the acquisition costs (stamp duty, legal fees), the cost of any capital improvements you made during ownership, and certain holding costs that were not previously deducted. This is where it is worth reading carefully, because not all holding costs are included in the cost base. Your accountant will determine the exact composition.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 12-month CGT discount</h2>
      <p>If you have held the property for more than 12 months, you are entitled to the 50% CGT discount as an individual investor. This means only half of your capital gain is included in your assessable income for that financial year. For a property that has appreciated significantly, this discount makes a material difference. A $400,000 capital gain becomes a $200,000 assessable gain, which is then taxed at your marginal rate.</p>

      <p>The marginal rate at which that gain is taxed depends on your other income in the year of sale. If you sell in a year where your employment income is at its peak, your gain will be taxed at the top marginal rate. If you sell in a year where your income is lower, such as after retirement or during a period of part-time work, the effective tax on your gain will be considerably lower. This is one of the most significant levers investors have, and it is worth modelling with your accountant before you commit to a campaign timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Do accumulated losses offset the capital gain?</h2>
      <p>This is one of the most common misconceptions. The annual losses claimed while negatively gearing the property were income tax deductions. They reduced your taxable income in the years they were claimed. They do not carry forward as an offset against your capital gain at sale time.</p>

      <p>There is a related concept worth understanding: capital losses. If you have realised capital losses from other assets (for example, from shares or a previous property sale that resulted in a loss), those losses can be used to reduce your capital gain on this sale. But operating losses from negative gearing are income tax offsets, not capital losses. The distinction matters, and getting it wrong leads to either unexpected tax bills or missed planning opportunities. Your tax accountant can map this for your specific situation before you sign an authority to sell.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Timing the sale to reduce CGT</h2>
      <p>There are several legitimate timing decisions that can reduce the CGT you pay. The most straightforward is the financial year in which you choose to settle. If you are approaching retirement, or planning a year where your income will be lower than usual, settling the property in that financial year means the capital gain is added to a lower base income. The effective tax rate on your gain could be noticeably lower than it would be in a peak-earning year.</p>

      <p>Settlement date is different from exchange date. The CGT event is triggered when the contract becomes unconditional, not when you sign it. If you exchange late in one financial year and settle early in the next, the gain is assessed in the financial year of exchange. Your accountant can confirm the exact position for your contract structure.</p>

      <p>Some investors also consider transferring a property to a self-managed superannuation fund before sale, though this involves contribution caps, transfer duty, and trust law considerations that require specialist legal and tax advice. It is not a simple option, but for the right investor profile it can significantly reduce the effective tax rate on the gain.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why a tax accountant is essential before you go to market</h2>
      <p>The decision to sell an investment property is not just a real estate decision. The timing, the financial year of settlement, the composition of your cost base, whether any capital losses can be applied, and what other income you will have in the year of sale all interact in ways that can move your net proceeds by tens of thousands of dollars. These are not details to sort out after you accept an offer.</p>

      <p>Before you appoint an agent and agree to a campaign launch date, sit down with your tax accountant and run through the numbers. Get a clear picture of your estimated capital gain, the applicable discount, and the tax on that gain under different income scenarios. Then make the timing decision with that information in hand. The cost of that conversation is trivial compared to the potential savings or the potential surprises it prevents.</p>

